<subSubSection id="C9C6F1F7FF1FCECFFCD5FCF6DFE938A6" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8163A27CFF1FCECFFCD5FCF6DFE938A6" blockId="146.[810,1452,807,1304]" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF1FCECFFCD5FCF6D8F73F6F" bold="true" box="[810,932,807,833]" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF1FCECFFBF4FCF6DF2E3F6F" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[1035,1149,807,833]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="puelche">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF1FCECFFBF4FCF6DF2E3F6F" box="[1035,1149,807,833]" italics="true" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">A.puelche</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF1FCECFFB76FCF6D8363F4B" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." pageId="146" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp;Goloboff, 2018</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 62 D–F) resembles 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF1FCECFFB8BFC9DDFBA3F4B" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[1140,1257,844,870]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnus">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF1FCECFFB8BFC9DDFBA3F4B" box="[1140,1257,844,870]" italics="true" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">A. magnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF1FCECFFB08FC9AD8893FA4" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." pageId="146" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff, 2018</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 6 D–F) by the BTA medialy placed, differing by the embolus distally wide, as in 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF1FCECFFAE1FC45DEF83F80" box="[1310,1451,916,942]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laventana">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF1FCECFFAE1FC45DEF83F80" box="[1310,1451,916,942]" italics="true" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">A. laventana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="19E7BEF9FF1FCECFFCCDFC69D8C33FFC" box="[818,912,952,978]" captionStart="FIGURE 129" captionStartId="142.[136,235,1421,1445]" captionTargetBox="[176,1391,200,1372]" captionTargetId="figure-233@142.[151,1435,189,1397]" captionTargetPageId="142" captionText="FIGURE 129. Actinopus laventana sp. nov., male: A–C LZI M135: A. Copulatory bulb, prolateral; B. Copulatory bulb, dorsal; C. Copulatory bulb, retrolateral. PA-Paraembolic apophysis; BTA-Basal Tegular Apophysis; PAc-Prolateral Accessory keel; PI- Prolateral Inferior keel; PS-Prolateral Superior keel; Arrows: Serrated area. Paratype, female: D FCE-MY 977: D. Spermathecae, dorsal view. Scales lines: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5597508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5597508/files/figure.png" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">Fig. 129</figureCitation>
A–C), from which they Males differ from those of PA originating at PAc. Additionally, they resemble 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF1FCECFFA6CFC0CD8CF3834" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="patagonia">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF1FCECFFA6CFC0CD8CF3834" italics="true" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">A. patagonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF1FCECFFC56FBD0DE473835" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." box="[937,1300,1024,1051]" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff, 2018</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 29 E–G) by PA continuous to PAc and 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF1FCECFFB83FBF4DE593811" box="[1148,1290,1061,1087]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laventana">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF1FCECFFB83FBF4DE593811" box="[1148,1290,1061,1087]" italics="true" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">A. laventana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF1FCECFFAE5FBF4DEFF3810" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[1306,1452,1061,1087]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="patagonia">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF1FCECFFAE5FBF4DEFF3810" box="[1306,1452,1061,1087]" italics="true" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">A. patagonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shape of the embolus with three keels in prolateral view and a developed serrated area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
